<div class="wrapper">

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">
      1. Movement-Language Primer
      <span class="glossary-tier-badge glossary-tier-badge--beginner">Beginner</span>
    </h2>
    <p>
      This glossary teaches how the freestyle language works: vocabulary,
      mechanics, and the compositional shorthand the community uses to name
      tricks. It is the &ldquo;how it reads&rdquo; layer &mdash; for the canonical
      catalog of named tricks, see the <a href="/freestyle/tricks">trick dictionary</a>;
      for the set-notation reference, see <a href="/freestyle/sets">/freestyle/sets</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The language is symbolic and compositional. Recurring movement structures
      compress into named operators; named operators stack onto base tricks to
      produce new ones. The same trick can usually be named at several depths
      &mdash; shortest readable form wins.
    </p>
    <p>
      The sections below progress from the body's vocabulary
      (&sect;2&ndash;&sect;4) to named structures (&sect;5), the operators
      that transform them (&sect;6), the notation that writes them
      (&sect;7), how tricks combine into runs (&sect;8), and how families
      relate across the dictionary (&sect;9). &sect;10 is the alphabetical
      reference; &sect;11 collects historical and community vocabulary.
    </p>
    <p class="detail-muted glossary-vocabulary-stabilization-note">
      The competitive freestyle vocabulary stabilized by roughly 2007&ndash;2008;
      no genuinely new base tricks have appeared in the corpus since. What
      this glossary documents, then, is a vocabulary that completed its
      first phase nearly two decades ago. Current work refines and recombines
      rather than expands. See the
      <a href="/freestyle/history">freestyle history page</a> for the
      two-phase story.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">
      2. Contact Surfaces &amp; Delays
      <span class="glossary-tier-badge glossary-tier-badge--beginner">Beginner</span>
    </h2>
    <p>
      A <strong>contact surface</strong> is where the foot or body meets the
      bag. A <strong>stall</strong> (or <strong>delay</strong>) holds the bag
      on a surface; a <strong>kick</strong> redirects it. Most stalls are
      1 ADD.
    </p>

    <h3 class="section-heading">Foundational surfaces</h3>
    <p>The two daily-driver surfaces that anchor most named tricks.</p>
    <dl class="glossary-term-list">
      <dt id="term-toe">Toe</dt>
      <dd>Top of the shoe, near the toe-box. The default surface for sets and many stalls. Often abbreviated <code>TOE</code> in operational notation.</dd>
      <dt id="term-clipper">Clipper</dt>
      <dd>The inside of the shoe near the arch &mdash; the cross-body surface. Clipper stalls implicitly involve a same-side (<code>SS</code>) cross-body position. Often abbreviated <code>CLIP</code>.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h3 class="section-heading">Foot surfaces</h3>
    <p>Less common as catch surfaces; appear regularly in specialized delays and named compounds.</p>
    <dl class="glossary-term-list">
      <dt id="term-inside">Inside</dt>
      <dd>The inner side of the foot. Used in inside-stall delays and as a transitional contact in compounds that travel across the body.</dd>
      <dt id="term-outside">Outside</dt>
      <dd>The outer side of the foot. Used in outside-stall delays; pairs with inside in same-foot transitions.</dd>
      <dt id="term-sole">Sole</dt>
      <dd>Bottom of the shoe. Stylistic and specialized; the surface for sole stalls and a number of cross-body variants.</dd>
      <dt id="term-heel">Heel</dt>
      <dd>Back of the shoe. Rare as a catch surface; appears in stylistic stalls and certain trick variants.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h3 class="section-heading">Body-region surfaces</h3>
    <p>Stylistic and specialized surfaces; most appear in named compounds rather than as default contact points.</p>
    <dl class="glossary-term-list">
      <dt id="term-knee">Knee</dt>
      <dd>Top of the knee. Used in knee stalls and knee-balanced positions during routines.</dd>
      <dt id="term-shin">Shin</dt>
      <dd>Front of the lower leg. Surface for shin stalls; see <a href="#term-cloud">cloud stall</a> for the canonical-active variant name.</dd>
      <dt id="term-neck">Neck</dt>
      <dd>Back-of-neck stall. Multiple variants distinguished by which side the bag enters and how the head tilts; most appear in routine choreography.</dd>
      <dt id="term-shoulder">Shoulder</dt>
      <dd>Top of the shoulder. Stylistic; appears in routine work and stall-chaining sequences.</dd>
      <dt id="term-chest">Chest</dt>
      <dd>Upper-chest stall. Stylistic and routine-oriented.</dd>
      <dt id="term-back">Back</dt>
      <dd>Upper-back stall. Specialized and rare; appears in advanced freestyle routines.</dd>
      <dt id="term-head">Head</dt>
      <dd>Top-of-head stall. Stylistic; appears in head-balance sequences and routine work.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h3 class="section-heading">Specialized variants &amp; alternative names</h3>
    <p>Named variants for specific surface-and-position combinations that the community treats as their own thing.</p>
    <dl class="glossary-term-list">
      <dt id="term-flapper">Flapper</dt>
      <dd>A cross-body sole stall (<code>XBD</code> + sole). The community name for the cross-body variant of a sole delay.</dd>
      <dt id="term-cloud">Cloud (cloud stall)</dt>
      <dd>The canonical-active name for a shin stall. &ldquo;Cloud&rdquo; is the surface label readers will see on trick pages; &ldquo;shin stall&rdquo; is the descriptive form.</dd>
    </dl>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">
      3. Dexterities (Dex)
      <span class="glossary-tier-badge glossary-tier-badge--beginner">Beginner</span>
    </h2>
    <p>
      A <strong>dex</strong> (dexterity) is a motion where the foot circles
      around the bag. The dex is the heart of freestyle &mdash; almost every
      named compound trick contains at least one.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Mirage uses one dex.</li>
      <li>Double Around the World uses two dexes.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="section-heading">Motion style</h3>
    <dl class="glossary-term-list">
      <dt id="term-hippy-leggy">Hippy vs leggy</dt>
      <dd>Every dex is one of two motion styles. A <em>hippy</em> dex draws its motion from the hip: the thigh circles the bag. A <em>leggy</em> dex draws its motion from the knee: the calf circles the bag.</dd>

      <dt id="term-x-dex">X-Dex</dt>
      <dd>A dexterity performed in a crossed-body position. The Atom Smasher, for example, uses an X-dex.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h3 class="section-heading">Direction</h3>
    <p>The arc a dex travels relative to the body. Direction pairs naturally with set primitives: <em>in-direction</em> dexes follow <em>pixie</em> and <em>quantum</em>; <em>out-direction</em> dexes follow <em>atomic</em> and <em>fairy</em>.</p>
    <dl class="glossary-term-list">
      <dt id="term-in-dex">In-dex</dt>
      <dd>A dex that travels <em>inward</em> &mdash; the bag arcs toward the body's center line. Paired with in-direction set primitives (pixie, quantum) and visible in compounds like Dimwalk (pixie butterfly) and Toe Blur (quantum mirage).</dd>

      <dt id="term-out-dex">Out-dex</dt>
      <dd>A dex that travels <em>outward</em> &mdash; the bag arcs away from the body's center line. Paired with out-direction set primitives (atomic, fairy) and visible in compounds like Atom Smasher (atomic mirage).</dd>
    </dl>

    <h3 class="section-heading">Execution window</h3>
    <p>The phantom space the leg draws around the bag while the dex is performed. The terms below describe where in that space the dex lives.</p>
    <dl class="glossary-term-list">
      <dt id="term-dex-window">Dex window</dt>
      <dd>The phantom space itself. The other terms in this subsection locate the dex within it.</dd>

      <dt id="term-deep">Deep</dt>
      <dd>A dex that sits high in the window, well away from the shoe. Controlled and clearly executed; the bag travels through a generous arc around the leg.</dd>

      <dt id="term-thin">Thin</dt>
      <dd>A dex that sits at the edge of the window, close to the shoe. The bag barely clears the leg; legal and counted, but the safety margin is small.</dd>

      <dt id="term-shoey">Shoey</dt>
      <dd>A dex that grazes the shoe surface during the circle. Distinct from a clean thin dex by the audible / visible shoe contact.</dd>

      <dt id="term-the">The</dt>
      <dd>A component whose motion misses the window entirely &mdash; the leg moves but the bag doesn't pass through. Typically counted as a fault.</dd>

      <dt id="term-scoopy">Scoopy</dt>
      <dd>A dex with extra under-bag character, where the leg cups beneath the bag during the circle rather than circling cleanly around it.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h3 class="section-heading">Execution quality</h3>
    <dl class="glossary-term-list">
      <dt id="term-clean">Clean</dt>
      <dd>Fully controlled, clearly executed. The reference quality every other label is measured against.</dd>

      <dt id="term-sloppy">Sloppy</dt>
      <dd>Poorly controlled execution. The dex completes but the motion is unclear or the bag's path is uneven.</dd>

      <dt id="term-pulled">Pulled</dt>
      <dd>A set or dex that drifts out of position mid-component. The bag pulls away from the intended path; recovery is possible but the component is no longer clean.</dd>

      <dt id="term-slurry">Slurry</dt>
      <dd>A dex completed too early &mdash; the leg finishes its circle before the bag has fully passed through the window.</dd>

      <dt id="term-froggy">Froggy</dt>
      <dd>Body motion begins before the set completes. The next component fires too soon; the trick reads rushed.</dd>

      <dt id="term-over-dexed">Over-dexed</dt>
      <dd>A dex with too much motion for what the trick requires &mdash; extra leg travel that doesn't serve the structure. Common in early learners working a new dex pattern.</dd>
    </dl>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">
      4. Timing Layers &amp; Sets
      <span class="glossary-tier-badge glossary-tier-badge--beginner">Beginner</span>
    </h2>
    <p>
      A trick has a clock. The <strong>set</strong> positions the bag; the
      bag rises, peaks, falls; the trick catches. Modifiers in &sect;6 are
      classified by which beat they transform.
    </p>

    {{! ── Timing-clock visual ──────────────────────────────────────────
        Horizontal "trick clock": the bag's parabolic arc maps onto the
        four-beat structure. Inline SVG; no client JS. Restrained palette
        consistent with the notation-token colors (#7f9a6b core-family green). }}
    <figure class="glossary-timing-clock-figure" aria-labelledby="timing-clock-caption">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 600 200" role="img" aria-label="A horizontal timeline showing the four-beat structure of a freestyle trick: set, uptime, midtime (peak), downtime, catch. The bag's path is drawn as a rising-and-falling arc." class="glossary-timing-clock">
        <line x1="50" y1="160" x2="550" y2="160" stroke="#bdb6a3" stroke-width="1.25" />
        <path d="M 80 160 Q 300 30, 520 160" fill="none" stroke="#7f9a6b" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" />
        <circle cx="80"  cy="160" r="5" fill="#7f9a6b" />
        <circle cx="190" cy="95"  r="5" fill="#7f9a6b" />
        <circle cx="300" cy="50"  r="6" fill="#5a7b48" />
        <circle cx="410" cy="95"  r="5" fill="#7f9a6b" />
        <circle cx="520" cy="160" r="5" fill="#7f9a6b" />
        <g font-family="inherit" font-size="13" fill="#3f3f3f" text-anchor="middle">
          <text x="80"  y="183">Set</text>
          <text x="190" y="118">Uptime</text>
          <text x="300" y="33"  font-weight="600">Midtime</text>
          <text x="410" y="118">Downtime</text>
          <text x="520" y="183">Catch</text>
        </g>
        <g font-family="inherit" font-size="11" fill="#8a8470" font-style="italic" text-anchor="middle">
          <text x="190" y="135">bag rising</text>
          <text x="300" y="68">peak</text>
          <text x="410" y="135">bag falling</text>
        </g>
      </svg>
      <figcaption class="glossary-timing-clock-caption" id="timing-clock-caption">
        The four-beat clock: a trick begins with a set, the bag rises through uptime, peaks at midtime, falls through downtime, and ends in a catch (stall or kick).
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <dl class="glossary-term-list">
      <dt id="term-set">Set</dt>
      <dd>The action used to position the bag before a trick. In modern usage, &ldquo;set&rdquo; refers to the uptime and midtime components together.</dd>
      <dt id="term-uptime">Uptime</dt>
      <dd>Before the peak. The bag is rising.</dd>
      <dt id="term-midtime">Midtime (hangtime)</dt>
      <dd>At the peak. The brief no-plant moment.</dd>
      <dt id="term-downtime">Downtime</dt>
      <dd>After the peak. The bag is falling toward the catch.</dd>
      <dt id="term-phases-sides">Phases and sides</dt>
      <dd>Tricks break into the three phases above by bag direction. A <strong>side modifier</strong> &mdash; same-side (<code>ss</code> / near) or opposite (<code>op</code> / far) &mdash; connects each component to its predecessor. <code>ss</code> is implied for clipper-led tricks; <code>op</code> for toe-led tricks.</dd>
    </dl>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">
      5. Core Trick Structures
      <span class="glossary-tier-badge glossary-tier-badge--intermediate">Intermediate</span>
    </h2>
    <p>
      The irreducible base tricks most other named tricks descend from. Each
      is a family anchor; most named compounds resolve to one of these once
      their modifiers and sets are stripped away.
    </p>
    {{> core-tricks-grid tricks=content.coreTricks idPrefix="term-"}}
    <p class="detail-muted glossary-network-attractor-note">
      Network analysis of 22 years of Sick3 sequences shows
      <a href="/freestyle/tricks/whirl">whirl</a> as the central attractor of the
      freestyle trick network &mdash; sequences converge on it as a stable
      resolution point. <a href="/freestyle/tricks?family=whirl">Blurry whirl</a>
      functions as the most common opening element. The transition
      <em>blurry whirl &rarr; whirl</em> is the most documented two-trick
      structure in the corpus.
    </p>

    <h3 class="section-heading">Trick families</h3>
    <p>
      A <strong>family</strong> is a group of tricks that share a
      <em>common terminal structure</em> &mdash; a conserved ending mechanic
      that every family member resolves through. The family base trick
      (e.g. <a href="/freestyle/tricks/whirl">whirl</a>,
      <a href="/freestyle/tricks/butterfly">butterfly</a>,
      <a href="/freestyle/tricks/mirage">mirage</a>) IS that terminal
      structure in its simplest form; modifiers and sets stack on top to
      create the full lineage of named compounds. Within a family, ADD
      difficulty climbs as more modifiers stack onto the anchor &mdash;
      the family becomes a difficulty ladder.
    </p>
    <p>
      Family membership is <strong>not</strong> the same as modifier or
      topology grouping. <em>Paradox</em>, <em>symposium</em>,
      <em>spinning</em>, <em>ducking</em>, and similar concepts are
      <strong>entry / topology / modifier systems</strong>, not terminal
      families &mdash; they describe what the body does mid-trick, but
      they do not share a conserved ending. Browse them via the trick
      dictionary's component view or topology view; their place is not
      inside the family hierarchy.
    </p>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      <em>Sibling terminal families.</em> Some families occur in pairs
      because they share a structural namesake but resolve through
      mirror terminal mechanics. The simplest sibling pair:
    </p>
    <ul class="glossary-family-sibling-pair">
      <li><strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks?family=whirl">Whirl</a></strong>: <code>leggy in dex &gt; ss clipper</code></li>
      <li><strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks?family=rev-whirl">Rev Whirl</a></strong>: <code>leggy out dex &gt; ss clipper</code></li>
    </ul>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      Mirror-pair siblings are not parent &amp; child &mdash; they resolve
      through inverse terminal mechanics. The Trick Dictionary surfaces
      sibling families adjacent in its family view.
    </p>

    <h4 class="section-heading">Root terminal families vs branch families</h4>
    <p>
      Two kinds of family-anchor object share the family view:
    </p>
    <ul class="glossary-family-kinds">
      <li>
        <strong>Root terminal families</strong> &mdash; primitive structural
        anchors with their own conserved terminal mechanic.
        <a href="/freestyle/tricks/whirl">whirl</a>,
        <a href="/freestyle/tricks/rev-whirl">rev-whirl</a>,
        <a href="/freestyle/tricks/butterfly">butterfly</a>,
        <a href="/freestyle/tricks/mirage">mirage</a>,
        <a href="/freestyle/tricks/osis">osis</a>,
        <a href="/freestyle/tricks/swirl">swirl</a>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Compressed branch families</strong> &mdash; named compounds
        that are themselves productive family anchors but also descend
        from a root terminal via a chain. <a href="/freestyle/tricks/torque">Torque</a>
        is a branch family rooted in osis lineage (&equiv; <em>miraging
        osis</em>). <a href="/freestyle/tricks/blender">Blender</a> &equiv;
        <em>whirling osis</em>. <a href="/freestyle/tricks/drifter">Drifter</a>
        &equiv; <em>miraging clipper</em>.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      Branch families surface as their own family sections in the
      dictionary; the underlying lineage is preserved via the chain
      reading on the family base&apos;s detail page. A branch family is
      a family in its own right AND a descendant of a root &mdash;
      both relationships are real and both are visible.
    </p>

    {{#if content.familyTrees.length}}
    <div class="glossary-family-trees" aria-label="Family-tree examples">
      {{#each content.familyTrees}}
      <div class="glossary-family-tree" id="family-tree-{{anchorSlug}}">
        <p class="glossary-family-tree-anchor">
          {{anchorDisplay}}
          {{#if anchorAdds}}<span class="glossary-family-tree-anchor-adds">{{anchorAdds}}</span>{{/if}}
        </p>
        {{#if members.length}}
        <ul class="glossary-family-tree-members">
          {{#each members}}
          <li>
            <a href="{{href}}">{{display}}</a>{{#if adds}}<span class="glossary-family-tree-member-adds">{{adds}}</span>{{/if}}
          </li>
          {{/each}}
        </ul>
        {{/if}}
      </div>
      {{/each}}
    </div>
    <p class="glossary-note">
      Four pilot families shown. The
      <a href="/freestyle/tricks">Trick Dictionary</a> groups all tricks
      by family (family-view toggle); the trick-detail page for any
      compound shows its family ladder so you can see siblings at a glance.
    </p>
    {{/if}}
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">
      6. Modifiers &amp; Operators
      <span class="glossary-tier-badge glossary-tier-badge--intermediate">Intermediate</span>
    </h2>

    {{! Operator-board visual orientation lives on the freestyle landing page; the
        glossary's role here is terminology and execution detail, not visual taxonomy. }}

    <p class="glossary-compositional-layering-note">
      Each modifier layered onto a base introduces a <em>simultaneous additional
      constraint</em> on body motion within a single set cycle. Difficulty therefore
      scales not linearly with modifier count, but through the interaction of
      multiple constraints. Two modifiers on a base are usually harder than the
      sum of their parts would suggest &mdash; the body has to satisfy both
      mechanics at once.
    </p>
    <p>A trick is typically composed of:</p>
    <pre><code>set &rarr; modifiers &rarr; base &rarr; catch (stall or kick)</code></pre>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Base trick</strong>: the core motion (e.g. mirage, whirl).</li>
      <li><strong>Modifiers</strong>: how the trick is altered (e.g. paradox, spinning).</li>
      <li><strong>Set</strong>: how the trick begins.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Examples:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Paradox Whirl = whirl (base) + paradox (modifier).</li>
      <li>Ripwalk = butterfly (base) + stepping (modifier).</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The glossary explains terms; the dictionary defines exact structure.</p>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      Some modifier weights have varied historically by era, region, and judge;
      the values below reflect the current Wave-1 ratified consensus. For the
      full accounting and discrepancy cases see
      <a href="/freestyle/add-analysis">ADD Accounting &amp; Analysis</a>.
    </p>

    {{! Movement-system preview preamble: surfaces the axis ontology at
        glossary-reading time so readers see the system before the modifier cards. }}
    <h3 class="section-heading" id="movement-system-axes">Movement-system axes (preview)</h3>
    <p>
      Modifiers cluster along four educational axes by what timing layer
      and body system they engage. The forthcoming
      <em>By Movement System</em> dictionary view groups tricks by axis;
      the modifier cards below are listed in cluster-paired form to
      surface the same structure.
    </p>
    <ol class="glossary-movement-system-axes">
      <li><strong>Set / Uptime Systems</strong> &mdash; launch mechanics + uptime dex character.<br>
        <em>pixie, fairy, atomic, quantum, nuclear, barraging, furious, blurry, stepping</em>.</li>
      <li><strong>Entry Topologies</strong> &mdash; entry relationship and cross-body framing.<br>
        <em>paradox</em>; positional vocabulary (op/ss, near/far, x-dex) lives in &sect;3 and &sect;7.</li>
      <li><strong>Midtime Body Modifiers</strong> &mdash; apex body mechanics around the trick&apos;s peak.<br>
        <em>spinning, ducking, diving, weaving, zulu, inspinning, gyro, tapping, whirling</em>.</li>
      <li><strong>No-Plant &amp; Suspension</strong> &mdash; body-discipline mechanics; the support leg leaves the ground.<br>
        <em>symposium, symple, muted, flying</em>.</li>
    </ol>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      The cards below surface a curator-selected pedagogical cohort
      (13 cards across 2 visual clusters); the full axis breakdown
      lives on the dictionary&apos;s movement-system browse surface.
    </p>

    {{! ── Surface A: Common Advanced Modifiers ─────────────────────────────
        Player-facing pedagogical view. Modifier cards in two clusters
        (set + body). Each card: name + optional glyph + feel + intuition
        + canonical example + optional family adjacency hint.
        Anchors at `modifier-{slug}`; complements the `term-{slug}` anchors
        in Surface B below. }}
    <h3 class="section-heading" id="common-advanced-modifiers">Common advanced modifiers</h3>
    <p>The modifiers players reach for most often. Read these for movement and feel; the structural readings live in the advanced reference below.</p>

    <div class="glossary-modifier-cluster">
      <h4 class="glossary-modifier-cluster-heading">Set / Uptime Systems</h4>
      <div class="glossary-modifier-cards">
        {{#each content.setModifierFeelCards}}
        <article class="glossary-modifier-card" id="modifier-{{slug}}">
          <p class="glossary-modifier-card-head">
            <span class="glossary-modifier-card-name">{{name}}</span>
            {{#if glyph}}<span class="glossary-modifier-card-glyph">{{glyph}}</span>{{/if}}
          </p>
          <p class="glossary-modifier-card-feel">{{feel}}</p>
          <p class="glossary-modifier-card-intuition">{{intuition}}</p>
          <p class="glossary-modifier-card-example"><em>Example:</em> {{example}}</p>
          {{#if familyHint}}<p class="glossary-modifier-card-family-hint">{{familyHint}}</p>{{/if}}
          <p class="glossary-modifier-card-tricks-link"><a href="/freestyle/tricks?view=component#component-{{slug}}">See tricks using {{name}} &rarr;</a></p>
        </article>
        {{/each}}
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="glossary-modifier-cluster">
      <h4 class="glossary-modifier-cluster-heading">Body Modifiers <span class="glossary-modifier-cluster-axes">(midtime &middot; entry &middot; suspension)</span></h4>
      <div class="glossary-modifier-cards">
        {{#each content.bodyModifierFeelCards}}
        <article class="glossary-modifier-card" id="modifier-{{slug}}">
          <p class="glossary-modifier-card-head">
            <span class="glossary-modifier-card-name">{{name}}</span>
            {{#if midtimeBody}}<span class="glossary-modifier-card-tag" title="Midtime body modifier — acts on the body around the trick's apex">midtime</span>{{/if}}
          </p>
          <p class="glossary-modifier-card-feel">{{feel}}</p>
          <p class="glossary-modifier-card-intuition">{{intuition}}</p>
          <p class="glossary-modifier-card-example"><em>Example:</em> {{example}}</p>
          {{#if familyHint}}<p class="glossary-modifier-card-family-hint">{{familyHint}}</p>{{/if}}
          <p class="glossary-modifier-card-tricks-link"><a href="/freestyle/tricks?view=component#component-{{slug}}">See tricks using {{name}} &rarr;</a></p>
        </article>
        {{/each}}
      </div>
      <p class="glossary-modifier-cluster-note">
        Cards above span three movement-system axes:
        <strong>spinning</strong> and <strong>ducking</strong> are
        midtime body modifiers (apex timing slot);
        <strong>paradox</strong> is an entry topology (cross-body framing);
        <strong>symposium</strong> is a no-plant / suspension mechanic.
        The forthcoming dictionary &ldquo;By Movement System&rdquo; view
        will group all members of each axis together.
      </p>
    </div>

    {{! ── Surface B: Advanced Decomposition & Operator Theory ─────────────
        Optional reference layer. Carries the structural-decomposition
        view of the modifiers above plus the four reference subsections
        the decomposition diagnostic and the formula table depend on.
        Anchors preserved (id="modifier-reference", id="intermediate-
        operators", id="execution-mechanics", id="set-modifiers-tier-1",
        and per-entry `term-{slug}`). }}
    <section class="glossary-advanced-reference-group">
      <h3 class="section-heading" id="advanced-decomposition-operator-theory">
        Advanced Decomposition &amp; Operator Theory
        <span class="glossary-tier-badge glossary-tier-badge--advanced">Advanced Reference</span>
      </h3>
      <p>
        Optional reference layer. Structural readings of the modifiers
        above plus the compositional vocabulary used in equivalence chains,
        formula derivations, and operational-notation analysis.
      </p>

      <h4 class="section-heading" id="modifier-reference">Body modifier reference</h4>
      <p>Structural definitions for the body-modifier cohort. The connective panels in &sect;9 surface each term's relationship to specific tricks.</p>
      <dl class="glossary-modifier-reference">
        <dt id="term-stepping">Stepping</dt>
        <dd>A foot-relocation modifier. The kicking foot relocates mid-trick, producing a stepping effect. Stacks with most bases. Stepping + butterfly = ripwalk.</dd>
        <dt id="term-paradox">Paradox</dt>
        <dd>
          A hip pivot between two dexes on the same set. +1 body modifier. The set leaves and returns to the same foot while the body changes sides in between.
          <span class="glossary-paradox-formula">Formula: <code class="notation-display-tokens"><span class="notation-token notation-modifier">PDX</span> &rarr; <span class="notation-token notation-surface">CLIP</span> &gt; <span class="notation-token notation-positional">OP IN</span> <span class="notation-token notation-dex">[DEX]</span></code> &mdash; clipper set, then a far in-out dex.</span>
          <a href="#glossary-panel-paradox">See connective panel</a>.
        </dd>
        <dt id="term-spinning">Spinning</dt>
        <dd>A full-body 360&deg; rotation carried through the dex moment. +1 body modifier. Pairs with gyro (180&deg;) for arbitrary degrees. <a href="#glossary-panel-spinning">See connective panel</a>.</dd>
        <dt id="term-ducking">Ducking</dt>
        <dd>A head dip that lets the bag pass around the neck. +1 body modifier; one member of a four-way family (ducking / weaving / diving / zulu) defined by head direction and the side the bag falls. <a href="#glossary-panel-ducking">See connective panel</a>.</dd>
        <dt id="term-symposium">Symposium</dt>
        <dd>A no-plant leg discipline: the support leg stays off the ground during the dex. +1 body modifier. Often stacks with paradox (the &ldquo;PS X&rdquo; shorthand).</dd>
        <dt id="term-cross-body">Cross-body</dt>
        <dd>A general descriptor for tricks (and components) where the active foot or dex crosses the body's center line. ADD category XBD covers cross-body components.</dd>
      </dl>

      <h4 class="section-heading" id="intermediate-operators">Intermediate operators &mdash; decomposition reference</h4>
      <p>Operators that decompose into combinations of other operators and Tier-1 primitives. Each entry shows its one-line meaning, its semantic decomposition where known, and worked examples. Entries flagged <em>pending</em> are under curator review. See also the <a href="/freestyle/sets">set notation reference</a> for the operational forms these operators produce.</p>
    <dl class="glossary-intermediate-operators">
      {{#each content.intermediateOperators}}
      <dt id="term-{{slug}}">
        {{name}}
        {{#if curatorConfirmPending}}<span class="glossary-operator-pending-flag">pending</span>{{/if}}
      </dt>
      <dd>
        <p class="glossary-operator-meaning">{{oneLineMeaning}}</p>
        {{#if decomposition}}
        <p class="glossary-operator-decomposition"><span class="glossary-operator-decomposition-label">Decomposes as:</span> {{decomposition}}</p>
        {{/if}}
        {{#if pendingNote}}
        <p class="glossary-operator-pending-note">{{pendingNote}}</p>
        {{/if}}
        {{#if workedExamples.length}}
        <p class="glossary-operator-examples">{{#each workedExamples}}{{#unless @first}} &middot; {{/unless}}<em>{{this}}</em>{{/each}}</p>
        {{/if}}
        <p class="glossary-operator-lineage">{{lineageNote}}</p>
      </dd>
      {{/each}}
    </dl>

    <h3 class="section-heading" id="execution-mechanics">Execution mechanics</h3>
    <p class="freestyle-section-sub">Mechanical details that operator names alone don't capture.</p>
    <dl class="glossary-execution-mechanics">
      <dt id="term-alpine">Alpine</dt>
      <dd>Divides a trick between its uptime and downtime, inserting a duck or dive between them. Alpine Ripwalk = Stepping Ducking Butterfly.</dd>

      <dt id="term-symposium-mech">Symposium (mechanic)</dt>
      <dd>A component where an active leg performs an action in a single-leg jump: the symposium leg jumps and lands on its own while the other leg remains in the air.</dd>

      <dt id="term-symple">Symple</dt>
      <dd>Starts symposium, but mid-component the non-symple foot returns to the ground. Naturally suits some compositions (e.g., Symp Legover). The shorthand <em>symp</em> can refer to either symposium or symple, whichever the component would naturally be done as.</dd>

      <dt id="term-muted">Muted</dt>
      <dd>An active leg held in the air for an entire component without planting. Mostly used for dexes, but applies to other components too.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h3 class="section-heading" id="set-modifiers-tier-1">Set modifiers (not core tricks)</h3>
    <p>
      Set modifiers are structural treatments applied <em>to</em> a base
      trick, not bases themselves. See the
      <a href="/freestyle/sets">set notation reference</a> for the full
      vocabulary.
    </p>
    <div class="glossary-set-modifiers-grid">
      {{#each content.setModifiers}}
      <article class="set-modifier-card" id="term-{{slug}}">
        <p class="set-modifier-head">
          <span class="set-modifier-name">{{name}}</span>
          {{#if glyph}}<span class="set-modifier-glyph">{{glyph}}</span>{{/if}}
        </p>
        <p class="set-modifier-meaning">{{oneLineMeaning}}</p>
        {{#if decomposition}}
        <p class="set-modifier-decomposition"><span class="set-modifier-decomp-sigil">&equiv;</span> {{decomposition}}</p>
        {{/if}}
        {{#if href}}
        <a class="set-modifier-deeplink" href="{{href}}" aria-label="Notation reference">&rarr;</a>
        {{/if}}
      </article>
      {{/each}}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section" id="notation">
    <h2 class="section-heading">
      7. Symbolic Notation
      <span class="glossary-tier-badge glossary-tier-badge--intermediate">Intermediate</span>
    </h2>
    <p class="glossary-thesis">
      The language evolves by compressing recurring compositional structures
      into shorter readable symbolic forms.
    </p>

    <p class="glossary-operator-notation-framing">
      Operational notation is the compact symbolic shorthand for trick
      composition. A trick like <em>paradox</em> reads as
      <code class="notation-display-tokens"><span class="notation-token notation-surface">CLIP</span> &gt; <span class="notation-token notation-positional">OP IN</span> <span class="notation-token notation-dex">[DEX]</span></code>
      &mdash; "clipper set, then a far in-out dex." The notation lets
      readers reconstruct the body mechanics from the trick name without
      having to memorize each compound separately. For the full operational
      grammar and worked decompositions see
      <a href="/freestyle/add-analysis">ADD Accounting &amp; Analysis</a>.
    </p>

    {{! ── Glyph quick-reference ──────────────────────────────────────────
        Visible-symbol strip at the top of §7 so the section opens with
        concrete glyphs rather than prose. Data sourced from
        content.operatorBoard.tiers; tier colors match the operator-board
        rendering on the landing surface. }}
    <div class="glossary-glyph-quickref" aria-label="Operator glyph quick reference">
      {{#each content.operatorBoard.tiers}}
      <div class="glossary-glyph-quickref-tier glossary-glyph-quickref-tier--{{key}}">
        <span class="glossary-glyph-quickref-tier-label">{{title}}</span>
        <ul class="glossary-glyph-quickref-list">
          {{#each operators}}
          <li class="glossary-glyph-quickref-cell">
            <span class="glossary-glyph-quickref-glyph">{{glyph}}</span>
            <span class="glossary-glyph-quickref-name">{{name}}</span>
          </li>
          {{/each}}
        </ul>
      </div>
      {{/each}}
    </div>

    {{! Notation in practice — three compact symbol-first examples.
        Static content; opens §7 with concrete tokenized formulas before
        the prose explainer. }}
    <div class="glossary-notation-in-practice" aria-label="Notation in practice — three compact examples">
      <p class="glossary-notation-row">
        <span class="glossary-notation-label">single base anchor</span>
        <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation"><span class="notation-token notation-core-family">whirl</span></code>
      </p>
      <p class="glossary-notation-row">
        <span class="glossary-notation-label">modifier + base</span>
        <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation"><span class="notation-token notation-modifier">paradox</span> <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">whirl</span></code>
      </p>
      <p class="glossary-notation-row">
        <span class="glossary-notation-label">deep compound</span>
        <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation"><span class="notation-token notation-modifier">stepping</span> <span class="notation-token notation-modifier">ducking</span> <span class="notation-token notation-modifier">paradox</span> <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">torque</span></code>
        <span class="glossary-notation-shorthand">&equiv; <strong>gauntlet</strong> (7 ADD)</span>
      </p>
    </div>

    <p>
      The longer you stack operators on a base, the longer the name &mdash;
      until the community converges on a shorter shorthand. Jobs notation
      is that shorthand made legible. A trick called &ldquo;mobius&rdquo;
      decompresses to &ldquo;spinning ss torque&rdquo;, and further to
      &ldquo;spinning ss miraging osis&rdquo;. All three forms are
      legitimate; the community uses the shortest readable one. See the
      <a href="#symbolic-compression-flow">symbolic-compression flow in &sect;8</a>
      for a worked example.
    </p>
    {{! Operator → named-compound block. Five compact compositions, all
        visible-token, demonstrate how operators stacked on bases produce
        the named tricks that appear in the dictionary. }}
    <p>Notation makes composition visible. Operator + base &rarr; named compound:</p>
    <div class="glossary-notation-mappings" aria-label="Operator → named compound mappings">
      <p class="glossary-notation-row">
        <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation"><span class="notation-token notation-set">pixie</span> + <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">butterfly</span></code>
        <span class="glossary-notation-shorthand">&rarr; <strong>DIMWALK</strong></span>
      </p>
      <p class="glossary-notation-row">
        <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation"><span class="notation-token notation-modifier">stepping</span> + <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">butterfly</span></code>
        <span class="glossary-notation-shorthand">&rarr; <strong>RIPWALK</strong></span>
      </p>
      <p class="glossary-notation-row">
        <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation"><span class="notation-token notation-modifier">paradox</span> + <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">whirl</span></code>
        <span class="glossary-notation-shorthand">&rarr; <strong>PARADOX WHIRL</strong></span>
      </p>
      <p class="glossary-notation-row">
        <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation"><span class="notation-token notation-set">pixie</span> + <span class="notation-token notation-modifier">ducking</span> + <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">butterfly</span></code>
        <span class="glossary-notation-shorthand">&rarr; <strong>PHOENIX</strong></span>
      </p>
      <p class="glossary-notation-row">
        <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation"><span class="notation-token notation-modifier">spinning</span> + <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">torque</span></code>
        <span class="glossary-notation-shorthand">&rarr; <strong>MOBIUS</strong></span>
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3>A beginner example: <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation">{{#with content.notationExamples.whirl}}{{#each tokens}}<span class="notation-token notation-{{cssRole}}" data-role="{{role}}" title="{{label}}">{{text}}</span>{{#unless @last}} {{/unless}}{{/each}}{{/with}}</code></h3>
    <p>
      A trick whose notation is just <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation">{{#with content.notationExamples.whirl}}{{#each tokens}}<span class="notation-token notation-{{cssRole}}" data-role="{{role}}" title="{{label}}">{{text}}</span>{{/each}}{{/with}}</code>
      is itself the family anchor. It carries one body rotation and resolves
      at its catch &mdash; no modifiers stacked on, no set primitive prefacing it.
      A single token tells you: this is the structural root.
    </p>

    <h3>A compound example: <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation">{{#with content.notationExamples.paradoxWhirl}}{{#each tokens}}<span class="notation-token notation-{{cssRole}}" data-role="{{role}}" title="{{label}}">{{text}}</span>{{#unless @last}} {{/unless}}{{/each}}{{/with}}</code></h3>
    <p>
      A whirl with the paradox modifier applied. The notation reads
      left-to-right exactly as the trick is built: the modifier (yellow-olive)
      shapes the body position; the base anchor (green) provides the rotation
      and family identity. Adds 1 ADD on top of whirl's base difficulty.
    </p>

    <h3>A modifier-heavy example: <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation">{{#with content.notationExamples.gauntlet}}{{#each tokens}}<span class="notation-token notation-{{cssRole}}" data-role="{{role}}" title="{{label}}">{{text}}</span>{{#unless @last}} {{/unless}}{{/each}}{{/with}}</code></h3>
    <p>
      Three body modifiers stacked on a torque base &mdash; known to the
      community as Gauntlet, a 7-ADD trick. Reading the notation
      left-to-right reveals the layered construction: each modifier
      contributes its own +1 to the total difficulty.
    </p>

    <h3 id="notation-roles">Color-coded structural roles</h3>
    <p>
      The visual hierarchy is restrained &mdash; only the four primary roles
      (core family, set, rotation, body modifier) carry color saturation.
      Hover any token on a trick page to see its role and resolved family name.
    </p>

    <h3 id="abbreviations">Abbreviations</h3>
    <p>Shorthand commonly seen in trick names and in operational notation. The two lists below separate the two contexts; a few abbreviations appear in both, listed under their primary domain.</p>

    <h4>Trick-name shorthand</h4>
    <p class="freestyle-section-sub">The shorthand that appears in trick titles and composition prose.</p>
    <div class="moves-table-wrap">
      <table class="moves-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Abbreviation</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {{#each content.abbreviations.trickNames}}
          <tr><td><code>{{short}}</code></td><td>{{meaning}}</td></tr>
          {{/each}}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h4>Operational-notation tokens</h4>
    <p class="freestyle-section-sub">The bracket-flagged component tokens that appear inside operational notation strings.</p>
    <div class="moves-table-wrap">
      <table class="moves-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Abbreviation</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {{#each content.abbreviations.operationalTokens}}
          <tr><td><code>{{short}}</code></td><td>{{meaning}}</td></tr>
          {{/each}}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    {{! ── Operational notation: advanced subsection ───────────────────────
        Per the v5 scaffold, operational notation is the execution-mechanics
        layer; kept here as an advanced reference subsection rather than a
        top-level section so the page reads primer-first. }}
    <h3 class="section-heading" id="operational-notation">
      Operational notation
      <span class="glossary-tier-badge glossary-tier-badge--advanced">Advanced Reference</span>
    </h3>

    <table class="glossary-layer-contrast">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Layer</th><th>Describes</th><th>Renders as</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Semantic</strong></td>
          <td>Compositional structure &mdash; what the trick <em>is</em></td>
          <td>Operator stack (e.g., <code>stepping ducking paradox torque</code>)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Operational</strong></td>
          <td>Execution mechanics &mdash; what the body <em>does</em></td>
          <td>Bracket-flagged sequence (e.g., <code>CLIP &gt; OP IN [DEX] &gt; OP OUT [DEX] &gt; [DEL] CLIP</code>)</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      The two layers are complementary, not interchangeable. The same trick
      may be named at several semantic stopping depths yet still have a
      single canonical operational form. Trick-detail pages render both
      side-by-side when both are authored.
    </p>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      Operational notation lives behind the &ldquo;Set notation (operational)&rdquo; section on per-trick pages. The reference below is the token vocabulary for that surface.
    </p>

    <h4>Component flags</h4>
    <p>Square-bracket annotations on a move that mark which structural component is in play. Multiple flags may stack on a single move.</p>
    <dl class="operational-glossary">
      <dt id="op-flag-dex"><code>[DEX]</code></dt>
      <dd>Dexterity component &mdash; the move involves bag-foot interaction (the foot circles around or contacts the bag).</dd>
      <dt id="op-flag-del"><code>[DEL]</code></dt>
      <dd>Delay component &mdash; the move ends in a stall on a foot or surface. Typically the final segment of an operational notation string.</dd>
      <dt id="op-flag-bod"><code>[BOD]</code></dt>
      <dd>Body-position component &mdash; the move includes a body pose change (spin, duck, dive, paradox).</dd>
      <dt id="op-flag-xbd"><code>[XBD]</code></dt>
      <dd>Cross-body component &mdash; the delay or move sits on the opposite-side surface from the plant foot. Typically appears with <code>[DEL]</code> on the landing.</dd>
      <dt id="op-flag-pdx"><code>[PDX]</code></dt>
      <dd>Paradox component &mdash; flags a cross-body far dex requiring a hip-pivot repositioning to bring the leg under the bag. Operationally: <code>CLIP &gt; OP IN [DEX]</code> (clipper set, far in-out dex). Equivalent to the <code>paradox</code> body modifier in semantic notation.</dd>
      <dt id="op-flag-xdex"><code>[XDEX]</code></dt>
      <dd>X-Dex component &mdash; a full-circle dex variant. In canonical usage, X-Dex applies only to specific named tricks; some external references use the flag more broadly.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h4>Sides</h4>
    <p>The side prefix on a move tells you which leg performs it relative to the plant foot.</p>
    <dl class="operational-glossary">
      <dt id="op-side-same"><code>SAME</code></dt>
      <dd>Same side as the plant foot. Roughly equivalent to the <code>SS</code> abbreviation seen in some trick names.</dd>
      <dt id="op-side-op"><code>OP</code></dt>
      <dd>Opposite side from the plant foot. The non-plant leg performs the move.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h4>Directions</h4>
    <p>The arc-direction tokens describe the bag's path during the dex.</p>
    <dl class="operational-glossary">
      <dt id="op-direction-in"><code>IN</code></dt>
      <dd>Inward arc &mdash; the bag travels toward the body.</dd>
      <dt id="op-direction-out"><code>OUT</code></dt>
      <dd>Outward arc &mdash; the bag travels away from the body.</dd>
      <dt id="op-direction-front"><code>FRONT</code> / <code>BACK</code></dt>
      <dd>
        Forward / backward direction. Standalone <code>FRONT</code> or
        <code>BACK</code> describes the arc; when followed by
        <code>WHIRL</code> or <code>SWIRL</code>, the two tokens fuse
        into a single rotational-variant move (e.g.
        <code>FRONT WHIRL</code>, <code>BACK SWIRL</code>).
      </dd>
    </dl>

    <h4 id="op-sequence-operators">Sequence operators</h4>
    <p>The arrow tokens segment the operational notation into discrete sub-actions.</p>
    <dl class="operational-glossary">
      <dt id="op-seq-minor"><code>&gt;</code></dt>
      <dd>Sub-step boundary &mdash; continuous flow within a beat group. The next move follows directly from the previous one without major pause or replant.</dd>
      <dt id="op-seq-major"><code>&gt;&gt;</code></dt>
      <dd>Major step boundary &mdash; often signals a no-plant break, a beat change, or a body-action transition. Visually heavier than <code>&gt;</code>; typically pairs with <code>(no plant while)</code> on a following move.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h4 id="op-pre-states">Pre-move state flags</h4>
    <p>Lowercase parenthesized annotations that describe the body state during the next move.</p>
    <dl class="operational-glossary">
      <dt id="op-prestate-back"><code>(back)</code> / <code>(front)</code></dt>
      <dd>Backward / forward direction of the next body action. Most often seen with <code>SPIN</code>: <code>(back) SPIN [BOD]</code> = backward body spin.</dd>
      <dt id="op-prestate-no-plant"><code>(no plant while)</code></dt>
      <dd>The support leg does not plant during this segment. Common in dense compounds where the body is mid-air during the move.</dd>
      <dt id="op-prestate-rooted"><code>(rooted)</code></dt>
      <dd>Held / rooted position; no plant. Corresponds to the <code>rooted</code> set primitive in the modifier table.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h4 id="op-surfaces">Surfaces &amp; body actions (reference)</h4>
    <p>The remaining vocabulary is small enough to list verbatim:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>CLIP</code>, <code>TOE</code> &mdash; plant or landing surfaces</li>
      <li><code>SPIN</code>, <code>DUCK</code>, <code>DIVE</code> &mdash; body actions</li>
      <li><code>FRONT WHIRL</code> / <code>BACK WHIRL</code> / <code>FRONT SWIRL</code> / <code>BACK SWIRL</code> &mdash; rotational dex variants on a rotational base</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="detail-muted">
      For the broader set notation reference (set primitives like Pixie,
      Fairy, Atomic, Quantum and how they decompose), see
      <a href="/freestyle/sets">Set notation reference</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">
      8. Composition &amp; Decomposition
      <span class="glossary-tier-badge glossary-tier-badge--intermediate">Intermediate</span>
    </h2>
    <p>
      Above the single-trick level, tricks combine into longer sequences. The
      vocabulary below describes how tricks are <em>used</em>, not how they
      are defined.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Run</strong>: a continuous sequence of tricks.</li>
      <li><strong>Shuffle</strong>: alternating sides rhythmically.</li>
      <li><strong>Link / Transition</strong>: the connection between tricks.</li>
      <li><strong>Connector Trick</strong>: a trick commonly used to maintain flow. Whirl-family tricks often act as connectors.</li>
      <li><strong>Dropless</strong>: a run without drops.</li>
      <li><strong>Density</strong>: average ADD per trick in a run.</li>
      <li><strong>Shred Circle</strong>: a group format where players take turns performing runs.</li>
    </ul>

    {{! ── Symbolic compression — a worked example ──────────────────────────
        Anchor `symbolic-compression-flow` is preserved for inbound deep-links
        from external references. }}
    <h3 class="section-heading" id="symbolic-compression-flow">Symbolic compression &mdash; a worked example</h3>
    <p class="glossary-compression-one-liner">
      <strong>mobius = gyro torque = spinning same-side torque</strong>
    </p>
    <p class="glossary-compression-expanded text-muted">
      Expanded: spinning same-side miraging osis.
    </p>
    <p>
      Three names. One trick. The community uses the shortest readable form
      &mdash; <em>mobius</em> is what players actually say, though either
      expanded reading is no less correct. For a step-by-step walkthrough
      of how operators stack and how ADD totals are derived, see
      <a href="/freestyle/add-analysis">ADD Accounting &amp; Analysis</a>.
    </p>

    {{! ── Walking-family progression ────────────────────────────────────────
        Pedagogical pathway: seven named compounds that branch off the
        butterfly base, each adding or swapping one operator. Surfaces
        within §8 as a worked example of how a base trick anchors a
        family of compositionally-related tricks. Readings sourced from
        freestyleSymbolicEquivalences.ts. }}
    <h3 class="section-heading" id="walking-family-progression">Walking-family progression &mdash; a family worked example</h3>
    <p>
      Seven canonical compounds, each branching off the butterfly base
      by adding or swapping one operator. Read top-to-bottom for a tour
      of how the butterfly family climbs the difficulty ladder.
    </p>
    <ol class="glossary-walking-family-progression">
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/butterfly">butterfly</a></strong>
        <span class="glossary-walking-family-formula"><span class="notation-token notation-core-family">butterfly</span> <em>(base, 3 ADD)</em></span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/ripwalk">ripwalk</a></strong>
        <span class="glossary-walking-family-formula">&equiv; <span class="notation-token notation-modifier">stepping</span> <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">butterfly</span> <em>(4 ADD)</em></span>
      </li>
      <li>
