  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading" id="traditional-reference">
      10. Traditional Reference
    </h2>
    <p>These describe the language around tricks rather than the tricks themselves &mdash; run quality, event formats, the ADD system.</p>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      This section covers vocabulary that operates at the <em>run</em> and <em>competition</em> level rather than the <em>trick</em> level. Trick-level definitions live in &sect;1&ndash;&sect;9 of this glossary.
    </p>

    <h3 id="run-quality">ADD system &amp; run quality</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>ADD (Additional Degree of Difficulty)</strong> is
      <em>additive structural accounting</em>: each base trick has a weight,
      each modifier has a weight, and a trick's total is the sum. This isn't
      just a scoring convention &mdash; it's the same logic that lets the
      dictionary read a compound like <em>mobius</em> as "gyro torque"
      and have the ADD add up the same way (4 + 1 = 5). Run-quality
      tiers describe the difficulty floor of a <em>run</em>, not individual
      tricks.
    </p>
    <div class="moves-table-wrap">
      <table class="moves-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Term</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td id="run-quality-tiltless">Tiltless</td><td>All tricks in a run are at least 2 ADD.</td></tr>
          <tr><td id="run-quality-guiltless">Guiltless</td><td>All tricks are at least 3 ADD.</td></tr>
          <tr><td id="run-quality-tripless">Tripless</td><td>All tricks are at least 4 ADD.</td></tr>
          <tr><td id="run-quality-fearless">Fearless</td><td>All tricks are at least 5 ADD.</td></tr>
          <tr><td id="run-quality-beastly">Beastly</td><td>All tricks are at least 6 ADD.</td></tr>
          <tr><td id="run-quality-godly">Godly</td><td>All tricks are at least 7 ADD.</td></tr>
          <tr><td id="run-quality-genuine">Genuine</td><td>Guiltless excluding BOP tricks.</td></tr>
          <tr><td id="run-quality-bop">BOP</td><td>Butterfly, Osis, Paradox Mirage.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p class="glossary-cross-link">
      For a deeper walkthrough of how ADD values are built, worked examples,
      and discrepancy case studies, see the
      <a href="/freestyle/add-analysis">ADD Accounting &amp; Analysis</a> page.
    </p>

    <h3 id="format-terms">Competitive &amp; format terms</h3>
    <p>These describe event formats and play contexts.</p>
    <ul>
      <li id="format-routine"><strong>Freestyle Routine</strong>: a choreographed performance to music.</li>
      <li id="format-sick3"><strong>Sick3</strong>: a three-trick side format scored as the sum of ADD values, no execution credit. The cleanest window into maximum-ADD capability.</li>
      <li id="format-shred-30"><strong>Shred Contest (Shred:30)</strong>: a technical scoring format with timed runs.</li>
      <li id="format-big-trick"><strong>Big Trick / Sick, Big, Best</strong>: single or combo highlight formats.</li>
      <li id="format-circle"><strong>Circle Contest</strong>: a turn-based elimination format.</li>
      <li id="format-most-rippin"><strong>Most Rippin&rsquo; Run</strong>: a last-player-standing format.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

