  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">12. Sources</h2>
    <p class="glossary-about-framing">
      This glossary is the codification surface for a vocabulary that the
      footbag community built informally over four decades. It documents
      the language; it is not the source of authority for the language.
      The community speaks the vocabulary; this page records it.
    </p>
    <p>
      Definitions on this page draw on long-standing community usage and
      historical reference materials, rewritten for clarity and
      consistency. Authoritative trick-level definitions &mdash; ADD
      values, structural decomposition, modifier relationships &mdash;
      live in the <a href="/freestyle/tricks">Trick Dictionary</a>.
    </p>
    <p>The major source families that contribute to this vocabulary:</p>
    <ul class="glossary-sources-list">
      <li><strong><a href="http://www.footbag.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">footbag.org</a></strong> &mdash; the long-running community archive; trick lists, event records, and the foundational vocabulary catalogued there. See also the <a href="http://www.footbag.org/newmoves/list" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">historical per-trick move list</a>.</li>
      <li><strong>PassBack</strong> &mdash; the conceptual tutorial series that introduced and formalised much of the modern compositional vocabulary (set / modifier / body operator framings).</li>
      <li><strong><a href="https://www.footbagmoves.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">footbagmoves.com</a></strong> &mdash; observational catalogue of named tricks, alternate names, and rotational variants; informs the symbolic-grammar layer of this glossary.</li>
      <li><strong>AnzTrikz</strong> &mdash; Australian / New Zealand demonstration series; canonical references for many compound rotational variants.</li>
      <li><strong>Tricks of the Trade (<a href="https://www.youtube.com/@WorldFootbag" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">WorldFootbag YouTube</a>)</strong> &mdash; 42-lesson tutorial series; canonical visual references for many of the dictionary entries.</li>
      <li><strong>Jobs notation</strong> &mdash; the compact symbolic shorthand for composing trick names ("paradox whirl", "stepping butterfly", etc.) used throughout the dictionary and §7 of this glossary. A community-recognized notation tradition, not a single-author convention.</li>
      <li><strong>Historical WFA / NHSA records</strong> &mdash; pre-IFPA federation records that anchor several legacy naming conventions still in use.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      Definitions integrate the above sources without quoting any single
      one verbatim; where a term carries a contested decomposition, the
      authoritative trick page surfaces the open question explicitly.
    </p>
  </section>

